(1147, 458, '_elementor_data', '[{\"id\":\"4f691aa2\",\"elType\":\"section\",\"settings\":[],\"elements\":[{\"id\":\"328aadda\",\"elType\":\"column\",\"settings\":{\"_column_size\":100},\"elements\":[{\"id\":\"18f9df92\",\"elType\":\"widget\",\"settings\":{\"editor\":\"<!-- wp:paragraph -->\\n<p>On January 5, 1933, construction begins on the\\u00a0Golden Gate Bridge, as workers began excavating 3.25 million cubic feet of dirt for the structure\\u2019s huge anchorages.<\\/p>\\n<p>Following the\\u00a0Gold Rush boom\\u00a0that began in 1849, speculators realized the land north of\\u00a0San Francisco\\u00a0Bay would increase in value in direct proportion to its accessibility to the city. Soon, a plan was hatched to build a bridge that would span the Golden Gate, a narrow, 400-foot deep strait that serves as the mouth of the San Francisco Bay, connecting the San Francisco Peninsula with the southern end of Marin County.<\\/p>\\n<!-- \\/wp:paragraph -->\"},\"elements\":[],\"widgetType\":\"text-editor\"}],\"isInner\":false}],\"isInner\":false},{\"id\":\"822ebc8\",\"elType\":\"section\",\"settings\":{\"structure\":\"21\"},\"elements\":[{\"id\":\"a04a4be\",\"elType\":\"column\",\"settings\":{\"_column_size\":33,\"_inline_size\":null},\"elements\":[{\"id\":\"aa76c7f\",\"elType\":\"widget\",\"settings\":[],\"elements\":[],\"widgetType\":\"image\"}],\"isInner\":false},{\"id\":\"40d45f7\",\"elType\":\"column\",\"settings\":{\"_column_size\":66,\"_inline_size\":null},\"elements\":[{\"id\":\"50a4bc7\",\"elType\":\"widget\",\"settings\":{\"editor\":\"<p>Although the idea went back as far as 1869, the proposal took root in 1916. A former engineering student, James Wilkins, working as a journalist with the\\u00a0<em>San Francisco Bulletin,<\\/em>\\u00a0called for a suspension bridge with a center span of 3,000 feet, nearly twice the length of any in existence. Wilkins\\u2019 idea was estimated to cost an astounding $100 million. So, San Francisco\\u2019s city engineer, Michael M. O\\